Brazilian Stock Movers: Tele Norte, Usiminas, Cosan, Petrobras

-- B y   L e o n   L a z a r o f f
-- 
2011-03-04T21:37:44Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-04/brazilian-stock-movers-tele-norte-usiminas-cosan-petrobras.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in Sao Paulo trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 4 p.m. New York time. Preferred
shares are usually the most-traded class of stock.  The Bovespa Index fell 0.2 percent to 68,012.10 and ended
the week down 1.7 percent.  Tele Norte Leste Participacoes SA (TNLP4 BS),  Brazil ’s
biggest fixed-line phone company, fell 1.8 percent to 25.84
reais. The company known as Oi forecast lower profit margins in
2011 than in 2010. Oi plans to invest 5 billion reais ($3
billion) to 6 billion reais this year on operations. Fourth-
quarter net income was 284 million reais, below the mean
estimate of 355 million reais from three analysts surveyed by
Bloomberg.  Usinas Siderurgicas de Minas Gerais SA (USIM5 BS), Brazil’s
second-largest steelmaker, rose 3.8 percent to 20.80 reais,
lifting shares 14 percent in three days. Copper rose 0.7 percent
for the week, the first weekly gain in a month.  Cosan SA Industria & Comercio (CSAN3 BS), which controls
the world’s largest sugar-cane processor with Royal Dutch Shell
Plc, fell 1.1 percent to 26.44 reias as annual inflation in
Brazil quickened to 6.01 percent, the fastest pace since
November 2008, and the real rose 0.5 for the week.  Petroleo Brasileiro SA (PETR4 BS) rose 0.4 percent to 29.08
reais as it received an environmental license to transport
natural gas from Brazil’s largest oil field, paving the way for
the state-run producer to boost output from the deep-water
deposit.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Leon Lazaroff in New York 
